# Lesson 05

# Leave Good Notes

## Why this lesson exists

Memory fades.

Documentation endures.

Every engineer eventually meets the same person again:

Future Me.

The notes you write today become the guide that helps you tomorrow.

Documentation is not extra work.

It is part of the work.

Clear documentation transforms mistakes into knowledge, experiments into reusable solutions and individual experiences into lasting understanding.

---

## The Question

How do I preserve today's understanding so Future Me can build on it tomorrow?

---

## Learning Objectives

By the end of this lesson you should be able to:

- explain why documentation is an essential engineering skill;
- distinguish between documenting actions and documenting understanding;
- identify what should be documented and what should not;
- create documentation that is useful to Future You;
- establish documentation habits that support future Adventures.

---

## Understand

Imagine someone hands you a machine.

It works perfectly.

But there are no labels.

No diagrams.

No explanations.

No history.

No one remembers how it was built.

Now imagine a second machine.

Alongside it is a notebook.

Every decision is explained.

Every mistake is recorded.

Every improvement is documented.

Which machine would you rather inherit?

Documentation is an act of kindness.

Because good documentation reduces the number of times a problem needs to be solved.

It shortens future investigations.

It prevents repeated mistakes.

It allows understanding to grow instead of restarting from the beginning.

The goal is not to document everything.

The goal is to preserve what would otherwise be lost.

---

## Practice

Think about the work you completed during Lessons 02 through 04.

For each document you created, ask yourself:

- Would Future Me understand this in six months?
- Have I explained *why* I made each decision?
- Have I recorded the assumptions behind my choices?
- Would another learner be able to follow my reasoning?
- Which details are unnecessary?
- Which important details are still missing?

Now revise one of your existing documents using those answers.

---

## Create Your Documentation Principles

Write a short set of personal documentation principles.

Examples might include:

- Explain the *why*, not only the *what*.
- Record decisions while they are fresh.
- Keep documentation close to the work it describes.
- Update documentation when reality changes.
- Leave every document clearer than you found it.

These principles should guide every future Adventure.

---

## Build Your Documentation Guide

Create a document containing:

```text
Documentation Guide

Purpose

Audience

Naming Conventions

Writing Principles

Folder Structure

Versioning Approach

Review Habit

Future Improvements
```

This guide becomes part of your persistent Lab documentation.

